# Create color palette
# Source: https://drsimonj.svbtle.com/creating-corporate-colour-palettes-for-ggplot2
bikeshare_colors <- c(
  aqua    = "#96ceb4",
  lite_yellow  = "#ffeead",
  red  = "#ff6f69",
  yellow    = "#ffcc5c",
  green   = "#88d8b0")

# Create function 
bikeshare_cols <- function(...) {
  cols <- c(...)

  if (is.null(cols))
    return (bikeshare_colors)

  bikeshare_colors[cols]
}


# Create Theme 
bikeshare_style <- function() {
  theme(
    axis.line = element_line(size = 0.05),
    text = element_text(family = "SourceSerifPro-Regular", face = "plain", 
                              colour = "black", size = 10, 
                              hjust = 0.5, vjust = 1, angle = 0, 
                              lineheight = 0.9), 
    plot.subtitle = element_text(family = "SourceSerifPro-Regular",
                               size = 8), 
    legend.background = element_rect(fill = "#DBDBDB", color = "black", size = 0.1),
    
    axis.text = element_text(family="SourceSerifPro-Regular",
                           size=8,
                           color="#222222"),
    axis.text.x = element_text(vjust = 1), 
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.major.x = element_line(color = "black", size = 0.1),
    panel.background = element_rect(fill = "#F2F2F2", colour = NA),
    
    strip.background = element_rect(fill = "white"),
    strip.text = element_text(size  = 22,  hjust = 0),
    plot.background = element_rect(colour = "white", fill = "#F2F2F2", size = 1),
    plot.margin = unit(c(2, 2, 1, 1), "lines")
  )
  }

On average, the South Side accounts for some of the shortest divvy bike trips in the city, while the West Side and Far Southeast Side account for some of the longest.

#parse date columns
divvy_date <- 
  divvy_census %>%
  mutate(dateatime = START.TIME) %>%
  separate(dateatime, into = c("date", "time", "ampm"), sep = " ") %>%
  separate(date, into = c("month", "day", "year", sep = " "))

# Create variable "distance_hav" which shows distance bikeride traveled (meters)
divvy_distance <- 
  divvy_date %>%
  filter(!is.na(Community.Areas)) %>%
  mutate(distance_meters = 
           distHaversine(matrix(
             c(FROM.LONGITUDE, FROM.LATITUDE), ncol = 2),
                                   matrix(
                                     c(TO.LONGITUDE, TO.LATITUDE), ncol = 2)))

divvy_distance %>%
  filter(!is.na(distance_meters)) %>%
  filter(year == 2018) %>%
  group_by(Chicago.side) %>%
  summarise(avg_distance_meters = mean(distance_meters)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(Chicago.side, avg_distance_meters), y = avg_distance_meters, 
             fill = Chicago.side), fill = "#2c7bb6") +
  geom_point() +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  labs(title = "The South Side accounts for the shortest average Divvy \ntrips within the City of Chicago",
    subtitle = "Average distance traveled by divvy trips in 2018",
    caption = "Chicago Data Portal Divvy Trip Data",
    x = "Chicago 'Sides'",
    y = "Average Divvy Trip Distance (Meters)") +
  coord_flip() +
  bikeshare_style()

  #scale_y_continuous(breaks = c(1, 2, 3))

Although the South Side accounts for some of the shortest bike trips in terms of distance, this area accounts for some of the longest trip duration in minutes. A divvy membership includes 30 minutes of â€œfree riding timeâ€ from bike check-out to return. In the majority of the Chicago areas, the average ride duration hovers just around the 30-minute mark, but the South, Southwest and West Side do not follow this trend.

divvy_date %>%
  filter(!is.na(Community.Areas)) %>%
  filter(year == 2014 | year == 2015 | year == 2016 | year == 2017) %>%
  filter(!TRIP.DURATION > 1440) %>% # Filter for bikes classified as stolen
  group_by(Chicago.side) %>%
  summarise(average_time = mean(TRIP.DURATION)/60) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_col(aes(x = reorder(Chicago.side, average_time), 
      y = average_time, 
      fill = as.factor(Chicago.side)), fill = bikeshare_cols("aqua"), 
    position = "dodge") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Divvy bike trip duration is greater in Chicago's \nNorth and South Suburbs",
    subtitle = "Average Divvy bike trip length from 2014 - 2017",
    caption = "Source: Chicago Data Portal Divvy Trip Data",
    x = "Chicago 'Sides",
    y = "Average Trip Time (In Minutes)") +
  bikeshare_style() +
  scale_y_continuous(expand=c(0,0), breaks = c(0, 2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 14))

Upon closer inspection of the three â€œChicago Sidesâ€ with higher than average rider time, you can see five Community areas that are responsible for increasing the average trip duration time for the South, Southwest and West side.

divvy_census %>%
  filter(!is.na(Community.Areas)) %>%
  filter(!TRIP.DURATION > 1440) %>% # Filter for bikes classified as stolen
  filter(Chicago.side == c("South Side", "Southwest side", "West Side")) %>%
  group_by(Community.Area.Name, Chicago.side) %>%
  summarise(average_time = mean(TRIP.DURATION)/60) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = average_time, 
             y = reorder(factor(Community.Area.Name), average_time), color = Chicago.side)) + 
  geom_segment(aes(yend = Community.Area.Name, xend = 0)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Five community areas in South, Southwest and \nWest Chicago account for above average trip time",
    subtitle = "Average divvy bike trip length from 2013 - 2018 in South, \nSouthwest and West Side Chicago Commuity Areas",
    caption = "Chicago Data Portal Divvy Trip Data",
    x = "Average Trip Time by Community Area (Minutes)",
    y = " ") +
  labs(fill = "Chicago 'Sides'", 
       color = "Chicago 'Sides'") +
  bikeshare_style() +
  scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0,0))

This graph compares divvy ride time duration changes between 2014 and 2017. This shows a strong linkage between number of bike stations in an area and trip duration. All areas show a clear decline in the average trip duration as the number of stations increase.

divvy_stations_year <- 
  divvy_date %>%
  filter(!is.na(Community.Areas)) %>%
  group_by(Chicago.side, year) %>%
  distinct(FROM.STATION.ID) %>%
  summarise(n_stations = n()) 

divvy_date %>%
  filter(!is.na(Community.Areas)) %>%
  filter(year == c(2014, 2017)) %>%
  group_by(Chicago.side, year) %>%
  summarise(average_trip_time = mean(TRIP.DURATION)) %>%
  left_join(divvy_stations_year, by = c("Chicago.side", "year")) %>%
  arrange(Chicago.side, year) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = average_trip_time, group = Chicago.side, 
             size = n_stations, 
             color = as.factor(Chicago.side))) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  labs(title = "Average ride time reduces as number of stations increase",
    subtitle = "Average trip time comparios across all eight 'Chicago Sides' in 2014 and 2017",
    caption="Chicago Data Portal Divvy Trip Data",
    x="Year",
    y="Divvy Trip Time (In Seconds)",
    color = "Chicago 'Side'",
    size = "Number of Stations") +
  bikeshare_style()

Share of the cityâ€™s population does not directly correlate with share of the cityâ€™s divvy ridership. for example, The South Side makes up less than 10% of the cityâ€™s population, but accounts for over 40% of the rides in 2018.

div_area <- 
  divvy_date %>%
  filter(!is.na(Community.Areas)) %>%
  filter(year == 2014 | year == 2015 | year == 2016 | year == 2017) %>%
  group_by(Community.Areas) %>%
  summarise(pop = unique(Total.Population), 
            n_rides = n()) %>%
  left_join(chi_ca, by = "Community.Areas") %>%
  group_by(Chicago.side) %>%
  summarise(sum_pop = sum(pop), 
            sum_rides = sum(n_rides)) %>%
  mutate(perc_rides = (sum_rides / sum(sum_rides) * 100), 
            perc_pop = (sum_pop / sum(sum_pop)) * 100)

div_area %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = perc_pop, y = perc_rides)) +
  geom_point(size = 1) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  geom_label_repel(aes(label=Chicago.side), color = "#2c7bb6") +
  labs(title="The South Side sccounts for less than 10% of the \npopulation, but accounts for over 40% of rides",
    subtitle="Divvy Ridership from 2014 - 2017",
    caption="Chicago Data Portal Divvy Trip Data",
    x="Chicago Population (by percentage)",
    y="Divvy Bike Rideshare (by percentage)") +
  bikeshare_style() +
  scale_x_continuous(expand=c(0,0), breaks = c(0, 5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30))

Map of bus station locations around the City of Chicago

# Clean l_stop data
#Seperate location variable into latitude and longitude variable
l_stop <- 
  l_stop %>%
  separate(Location, into = c("lat", "lon"), sep = ",") %>%
  mutate(lat = str_remove(lat, "\\(")) %>%
  mutate(lon = str_remove(lon, "\\)"))

# Rename lattitude and longitude lines
cta_bus <- 
  cta_bus %>%
  rename("lon" = "POINT_X") %>%
  rename("lat" = "POINT_Y")

# grab a center/zoom map and compute its bounding box
chi_map <- ggmap(get_googlemap(center = c(-87.682571,41.888605),
                    zoom = 11, scale = 2,
                    maptype ='terrain',
                    color = 'color'))

# Map of bus stops
chi_map + geom_point(aes(x = lon, y = lat,  colour = "red"), 
                     data = cta_bus, size = 0.5) + 
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")
